1. e4 c5 {Sicilian Defense} 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {Najdorf Variation} 6. h3 {I got this idea from Fischer's book "My 60 Memorable Games"} e5 7. Nde2 Be6 8. g4 Be7 9. g5 Nfd7 10. h4 O-O {Castling into it} 11. Ng3 f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 {Very bad: this gives the white knight an outpost on d5.} 13. Nxf5 Rxf5 14. Bh3 Rf8 15. Nd5 Nc6 16. c3 {Black is weak on the light squares and his darksquare bishop might as well be a pawn. Notice how the black bishop never makes another move for the rest of the game.} Nb6 {What else?} 17. Be3 Nxd5 18. Qxd5+ Kh8 19. O-O-O Qc7 20. Kb1 {avoiding the threat of Nb4} b5 21. Bg2 Rac8 22. Be4 b4 23. c4 a5 24. b3 Nd8 25. h5 Nf7 {losing} 26. g6 Ng5 27. h6 Nxe4 28. hxg7+ Kxg7 29. Rxh7+ Kxg6 30. Qxe4+ Rf5 {Now black loses a rook and will get mated.} 31. Rh6+ {Gameover} 